# User Centric Front End Development Milestone Project - The Monkees

The monkees were an American rock and pop band who were originally active
between 1966 and 1971. With the reunions, albums and tours in the decades that
followed, it was clear that they would go down in history as one of the
originators of pop rock.

This website hopes to capture The Monkees as a band, their members and the rich
history they had. Thank you for visiting the site and below is some more
information on the website.

## UX

This website is focusing on a wide variety of people who all have a love or
interest in The Monkees, who are fans of rock and pop, or who are a fan of music
from the 60s to 80s.  This website can be used for research purposes, to learn
more about The Monkees or by people who have an interest in what they have
achieved or done during their career.  The information is split into four pages
to help the user soak in the information in an effective manner.

Below are a list of user stories written to help plan the website:

 - As a Monkees fan, I want to clearly see the band members, so I can learn more about them.
 - As a researcher, I would like to see the history of the band, so that I can write a paper on them.
 - As a general user, I would like the information to be clean and clear, so that I have a comfortable experience using the site.
 - As a Monkees fan, I want to be able to see their official social accounts, so I can keep up to date with them.
 - As a mobile phone user, I would like the website to be scaled nicely to fit my device.

## Features

### Existing Features

 - Header Image - allows the user to return to the index.html page by clicking the image.
 - Header Menu - allows the user to navigate the website by clicking one of the four buttons.
 - Footer Menu - allows the user to navigate the website while in desktop mode.
 - Footer Social Links - allows the user to navigate the appropriate social accounts by automatically opening a new tab.

### Features Left To Implement

 - Contact Form - It will allow the user to send a message about the monkees.

## Testing

For testing the website, I have taken three approaches; manual testing, using a
validator and running a google chrome audit.

For manual testing, I clicked on each individual link to make sure that they
worked and tried clicking them in different orders.

For using a validator, I used [W3C validator](https://validator.w3.org/). I ran
each page of the site through it and changed what needed to be changed.

For google chrome audit, I right clicked on the page, clicked on inspect and went
to audit.  From there I clicked run and it split the information into 5 categories.
Out of these 5, I got 3 of them to 100% and performance to 99%.

## Deployment

For deploying the webpage I used [GitHub](https://github.com/). It was all stored
onto one branch and 23 commits were made.

There are no differences between the deployed and local version of the site that I
have.
